cp|red|at|^*bOliverC:^*n|cp||at|   One thing worth noting: For the purposes of ANY Beta Ask, Singleton Kings are generally @CNOT@C included in our tally of controls @HUNLESS@H we have a good indication from the previous bidding that it's likely to be carrying a decent amount of its "normal weight" (eg: partner has SHOWN that suit).

Suppose you hold    @SK  @HAQJxx  @DQxxx  @CKxx

Partner opens 1@C and the bidding proceeds 

^c 1@C  -  1@H  -  1NT(Low-level Beta)  -  ???     Here you should show THREE controls only.

On the other hand, suppose the bidding starts 

^c 1@C  -  1@H  -  1@S(Alpha)  -  ???      Now you should show FOUR controls, because partner's Ask in Spades makes it MUCH more likely that your @SK really is worth something.

Another time you MIGHT consider counting a singleton King is when partner has shown a very strong balanced hand (24+).

That's just on the balance of probabilities that partner is much more likely to have the Ace and/or Queen of that suit.

Generally, though, we do NOT count singleton Kings as a control.   Indeed I tend not to count singleton K, Q or J in my HCP when evaluating my hand.

Please do not worry if you can't recall the scales in detail.   Have a read through the notes on the Website and perhaps print them out.

Gradually they will make sense and settle down in your memory.|
